00:05:40.870 --> 00:05:43.060
You know, it's funny
though, because this thing

00:05:43.060 --> 00:05:46.120
that we think is a good thing--
a little parenthetical point I

00:05:46.120 --> 00:05:49.370
want to make-- was not always
thought that way at all.

00:05:49.370 --> 00:05:52.880
This is Lord Chesterfield
in a letter to his son,

00:05:52.880 --> 00:05:54.080
how to conduct himself.

00:05:54.080 --> 00:05:56.240
Frequent and loud laughter
is the characteristic

00:05:56.240 --> 00:05:57.690
of folly and ill manners.

00:05:57.690 --> 00:05:59.530
How low and unbecoming
a thing laughter

00:05:59.530 --> 00:06:02.090
is, not to mention the
disagreeable noise that it

00:06:02.090 --> 00:06:03.870
makes, and the
shocking distortion

00:06:03.870 --> 00:06:05.120
of the face that is occasions.

00:06:05.120 --> 00:06:08.570
I have never laughed in my life.

00:06:08.570 --> 00:06:10.500
It's interesting,
our view of laughter

00:06:10.500 --> 00:06:12.470
and the importance
of it has changed.

00:06:12.470 --> 00:06:16.150
I can show you
that by, well, this

00:06:16.150 --> 00:06:19.656
is Plato and Aristotle
and Hobbes' views of it.

00:06:19.656 --> 00:06:21.030
Mixture of pleasure
and pain that

00:06:21.030 --> 00:06:23.010
lies in the malice of amusement.

00:06:23.010 --> 00:06:25.130
Aristotle, comedy is
an imitation of people

00:06:25.130 --> 00:06:26.550
worse than themselves.

00:06:26.550 --> 00:06:29.840
Hobbes is all about
superiority theory.

00:06:29.840 --> 00:06:31.897
You'll be happy to see this.

00:06:31.897 --> 00:06:32.730
It's a Google Ngram.

00:06:35.320 --> 00:06:41.900
Nobody even had a sense
of humor until about 1870.

00:06:41.900 --> 00:06:42.930
Isn't that amazing?

00:06:42.930 --> 00:06:44.630
It's actually quite a new thing.

00:06:44.630 --> 00:06:46.600
It actually is a new thing.

00:06:46.600 --> 00:06:49.180
Before that, based
on what I showed you

00:06:49.180 --> 00:06:51.460
about Aristotle and
Plato, views of humor

00:06:51.460 --> 00:06:52.900
were very, very negative.

00:06:52.900 --> 00:06:53.500
Why?

00:06:53.500 --> 00:06:55.986
Because the thing that we
call the sense of humor,

00:06:55.986 --> 00:06:57.860
they said the thing was
called either a sense

00:06:57.860 --> 00:07:00.740
of the ridiculous or
a sense of ridicule.

00:07:00.740 --> 00:07:03.980
Because that's one of the
primary function of humor.

00:07:03.980 --> 00:07:06.170
There's wonderful functions
of humor, but when

00:07:06.170 --> 00:07:09.342
you think, well, why is it
in every culture, everywhere,

00:07:09.342 --> 00:07:10.050
and all the time?

00:07:10.050 --> 00:07:10.760
What does it do?

00:07:10.760 --> 00:07:11.680
What is its function?

00:07:11.680 --> 00:07:12.640
Why is it everywhere?

00:07:17.290 --> 00:07:21.180
You ask, what is it that keeps
everybody doing-- conforming,

00:07:21.180 --> 00:07:21.680
basically.

00:07:21.680 --> 00:07:24.190
Not at Google, but
everywhere else.

00:07:24.190 --> 00:07:25.750
What is it?

00:07:25.750 --> 00:07:27.681
You don't want to be
embarrassed, right?

00:07:27.681 --> 00:07:29.930
You don't want to have that
toilet paper on your shoe,

00:07:29.930 --> 00:07:32.229
you don't want to have
your fly open, right.

00:07:32.229 --> 00:07:34.270
We know what it's like to
be in elementary school

00:07:34.270 --> 00:07:35.620
and high school.

00:07:35.620 --> 00:07:37.510
What's the policeman
of embarrassment?

00:07:37.510 --> 00:07:38.570
Laughter.

00:07:38.570 --> 00:07:42.985
So one of the functions of
laughter-- a harsh function,

00:07:42.985 --> 00:07:46.220
a conforming
function-- is ridicule.

00:07:46.220 --> 00:07:47.742
People say laughter
is contagious.

00:07:47.742 --> 00:07:49.200
Well, that laughter
was contagious,

00:07:49.200 --> 00:07:51.462
but it's not contagious
when it's behind your back.

00:07:51.462 --> 00:07:53.920
So that's one of the reasons
it wasn't looked on favorably.

00:07:53.920 --> 00:07:56.275
Now it's very different,
because a sense of humor

00:07:56.275 --> 00:07:58.570
came to mean something else.

00:07:58.570 --> 00:08:01.040
What a sense of
humor came to mean--

00:08:01.040 --> 00:08:03.954
it's easier to see by what you
say if someone doesn't have it.

00:08:03.954 --> 00:08:06.120
Why do we say someone doesn't
have a sense of humor?

00:08:06.120 --> 00:08:08.150
It's more than they're
not funny, right.

00:08:08.150 --> 00:08:09.700
They have rigid thinking.

00:08:09.700 --> 00:08:11.990
They have no perspective
on themselves.

00:08:11.990 --> 00:08:15.040
The transformation is
why it became important,

00:08:15.040 --> 00:08:17.534
and why it's very difficult
for computers to have it.

00:08:17.534 --> 00:08:19.950
Because the sense of humor,
which originally was something

00:08:19.950 --> 00:08:23.900
that was directed out to
something deformed, something

00:08:23.900 --> 00:08:26.610
ugly that you didn't
have empathy for, got

00:08:26.610 --> 00:08:30.247
directed back towards ourselves
as something to be perspective.

00:08:30.247 --> 00:08:32.580
That's why it's valued, and
that's part of its function,

00:08:32.580 --> 00:08:33.610
now, also.

00:08:33.610 --> 00:08:35.780
What does evolution
tell us about humor?

00:08:35.780 --> 00:08:38.419
That's a little cartoon of mine.

00:08:38.419 --> 00:08:39.422
